Red wine quality EDA by Alfred Wong

Introduction

In this study we explore a dataset about wine quality created by Cortez et al. (2009) in:

P. Cortez, A. Cerdeira, F. Almeida, T. Matos and J. Reis. Modeling wine preferences by data mining from physicochemical properties. In Decision Support Systems, Elsevier, 47(4):547-553. ISSN: 0167-9236.

Available at:

[@Elsevier] http://dx.doi.org/10.1016/j.dss.2009.05.016

[Pre-press (pdf)] http://www3.dsi.uminho.pt/pcortez/winequality09.pdf

[bib] http://www3.dsi.uminho.pt/pcortez/dss09.bib

It has with 1599 observations of 12 variables.

Each observation is a bottle of the Portuguese Vinho Verde red wine. Our main feature here is the quality of the bottle, which is the median of integer (0-10) ratings given by at least three experts.

The rest of the features are measurements given by physiochemical tests. (The variable X shown below is just the index)

Our aim is to explore the data, paving the way for further studies to find out what features can help predict that a wine will be good.

Univariate Plots Section

Now lets take a look at the variables one by one.

quality

quality is the rating of the wine. 3 or more experts rated the wine from 0, the worst, to 10, the best, and the median is taken. All of the values we have are between 3 and 8, and mostly concentrated in 5 and 6. This will be the focus of our study, as our aim is to explore the variables affecting quality.

alcohol

alcohol is the alcohol content by volume. We see that most of our wines have values between 9 and 14, with a mean of 10.42 and a median of 10.20.

fixed.acidity

fixed.acidity is the amount of tartaric acid present in the wine. Most wines in our data set have around 8 gram per liter. The distribution have a bit of skewedness towards the right.

With the log transformation the distribution looks somewhat closer to normal.

volatile.acidity

volatile.acidity is the amount of acetic acid, in grams / liter. Usually it is associated with bad quality with its vinegar-y smell. The distribution looks bimodal, with peaks at around 0.4 and 0.6 g/L

citric.acid

citric.acid is the amount of citric acid in the wine, again in grams / liter. Many of the wines in our dataset has none at all. There are a few spots of concentrated frequencies at 0.49, 0.24 and 0.02. This is not a binning problem in our plot, as I have matched the binwidth with the data.

As for the other values, we have a few outliers at 1.00, and the rest are somewhat uniformly distributed up to around 0.5, and then gradually decrease.

pH

The pH value of the wine. The lower the value the more acidic is the wine.

The distribution is symmetric with a mean of 3.311.

Note that pH value itself is a logarithmic measurement of hydrogen ions, so at least chemically speaking, a wine with a pH value of 3 is ten times more acidic than one with a 4.

However, pH value is not exactly the log of (fixed.acidity + volatile.acidity), as the pH value is affected by both the amount and strength of acids present, while the acidity values count only the amount of the acids concerned.

residual.sugar

residual.sugar is the amount of sugar, in gram / liter, left in the wine after the fermentation process ends, or stopped by the winemaker.

Ceteris paribus, the more residual sugar there is, the sweeter the wine should taste. But then the sensation of sweetness is also affected by many other factors, such as acidity.

The majority of observations form a bell shape, with the rest forming a long tail to the right. The median is 2.2 while the mean is 2.54.

Again with a log scale the distribution looks more symmetric.

chlorides

cholorides is the amount of sodium chlorides (ie, salt) in the wine, in gram / liter. In large enough amounts they give the wine a salty taste. Most of the wines in our sample have less than 0.12 g/L, but some outliers have up to 0.6 g/L.

Here the log transformation makes the main part of the distribution less bell-like, but evens out the tails on both sides a little.

free.sulfur.dioxide

Sulfur dioxide is a by-product of the fermentation process, but is also added to the wine by the winemaker. It serves as 1. a anti-microbial agent that suppresses harmful yeast and bacteria growth, and 2. an anti-oxidatant to keep the wine fresh.

free.sulfur.dioxide is the amount that exists as molecular SO2, sulfite or bisulfite ions, that helps suppress microbes and oxidation. The unit is mg / liter.

The distribution of free.sulphur.dioxide has a tail to the right. But neither the logarithic or the square root transformation would make it very bell-shaped.

Like in this log-transformed plot.

total.sulfur.dioxide

Bound sulfur dioxide is the portion that is already attached to other compounds in the wine, and thus does not work as antimicrobial or antioxidant.

total.sulfur.dioxie is the total of free plus bound sulfur dioxide.

The distribution skews to the right, with a mean of 46.47 and a median of 38.

A log transformation makes it much more symmetric.

sulphates

sulphates is the amount of potassium sulphate in the wine, in gram / liter. It is an additive to increase the sulfur dioxide levels.

Again the logarithmic transformation makes the distribution more symmetric.

density

density is the density of the wine, in gram / ml.

The distribution looks quite normal, with the mean and median at 0.9967 and 0.9968 respectively.

Most of the wines have a density < 1, ie, lighter than water.

Univariate Analysis

The data set contains 1599 observations of 12 variables. One of them is quality, the focus of our study.

Given how few variables there are, well use all the other variables in our study, in hopes to find relationship with quality.

I have created the logarithmic transformations of fixed.acidity, residual.sugar, chlorides, total.sulfur.dioxide and sulphates for future use.

A bound.sulfur.dioxide.log10 is created by taking the logarithm of the difference between total.sulfur.dioxide and free.sulfur.dioxide.

Ive also binned quality into 3 categories, bad for quality 3 and 4, average for 5 and 6, good for 7 and 8. This will be used in multivariate analyses to reduce the number of colors used for better contrast.

Bivariate Plots Section

Pair plots

Lets first take a glance over the paired plots. From the box plots with quality, we can see that alcohol, volatile.acidity, citric.acid seem to show the strongest relationship with quality.

Well explore these pairs, as well as other pairs with high correlation one by one. The number below the plots between quality and other features are the Spearmans correlation coefficient, using quality as an ordinal factor.

alcohol and quality

## [1] 0.4785317

We can see quite an obvious positive relationship between alcohol and quality.

The spearmans correlation coefficient, at 0.48, is coherent with the observation.

Of course, this isnt to say that higher alcohol content necessarily makes the wine better, otherwise even the worst ports and sherries would trump the best wines.

Rather, it could be that better made wines happen to have higher alcohol content, due to a third factor.

volatile.acidity and quality

## [1] -0.3806465

Unsurprisingly, volatile.acidity shows a negative correlation with quality, at -0.38.

Acetic acid, with its vinegar-y smell, is quite universally agreed upon as unpleasant in wine.

citric.acid and quality

## [1] 0.2134809

The relationship betwen citric.acid and quality is less clear. The coefficient is 0.21.

chlorides.log10 and quality

## [1] -0.1899223

Again the relationship here is faint, with spearmans coefficient at 0.19. I expected it to be stronger as saltiness is certainly a negative trait for most people.

Sulphur dioxides and quality

## [1] -0.1967351

## [1] -0.2333584

## [1] -0.05690065

None of the 3 variables we have about sulfur dioxide free.sulfur.dioxide, bound.sulfur.dioxide and total.sulfur.dioxide, are highly correlated to quality by themselves. The spearmans coefficient are around 0.2.

But all of them seem to show a parabolic relationship with quality, if the latter is to be interpreted as a continuous variable.

This may warrant further investigation, or some feature engineering.

sulphates and quality

## [1] 0.3770602

With sulphates we see quite a clear positive relationship with quality, with spearmans coefficient at 0.38.

density and quality

## [1] -0.1770741

The relationship between density and quality is quite weak.

Also, density is highly correlated to many other variables we have, which, in turn, are correlated to quality. It is doubtful if density is still meaningful if those other variables are accounted for.

citric.acid and fixed.acidity

This is one of the strongly correlated pairs among all the variables we have.

fixed.acidity.log10 and pH

As one would expect, fixed.acidity has a strong negative correlation with pH.

volatile.acidity and pH

A little surprising is that volatile.acidity is slightly positively correlated with pH, at 0.235.

alcohol and density

Density is correlated with many of our variables, one of which is alcohol. The negative correlation makes sense, as alcohol is less dense than water.

fixed.acidity.log10 and density

Correlation coefficient is 0.675.

residual.sugar.log10 and density

This plot may look a bit quirky, but in the left half of the plot that contains most of the observations, density actually shows a monotonic relationship with residual.sugar .

Bivariate Analysis

Among the variables we have, we can see that quality is most strongly correlated with alcohol, followed by volatile.acidity and sulphates. Some other variables with weaker correlation are citric.acid, chlorides and bound.sulfur.dioxide.

The acid-related variables are often correlated with each other, and with pH as well, which makes sense. The odd one is volatile.acidity, which is negatively correlated with the other acid volumes and positively with pH.

Density is highly correlated with many variables such as fixed.acidity and alcohol.

The pair of variables with the strongest correlation is free.sulfur.dioxide and total.sulfur.dioxide.log10, with a coefficient of 0.714.

Multivariate Plots Section

The top 3 features and quality

With two of our variables with the strongest correlation with quality, we can see the pattern clearly in this plot. alcohol and sulphates correlate positively with quality

Again we can see that as the quality increases from blue to red, we go from the top left to bottom right in this plot, ie, lower volatile.acidity and higher alcohol.

The patter is less pronounced in this plot as neither of the two variables here are as strongly correlated to quality as alcohol. But still the pattern is visible.

alcohol, density and quality

In this plot I use the binned quality (4 and below are bad, 5 and 6 average, 7+ are good). We lose some information details but this way the contrast is better and the pattern easier to see.

We can see that density has a negative relationship with alcohol, as alcohol is less dense than water. And it seems that among wines with the same alcohol content levels, the relationship between density and quality almost reverses, ie, the higher the density, the higher the quality.

Id speculate that the negative correlation between density and quality is completely explained by its negative correlation with alcohol.

Acidities and pH

Lastly we take a look at how pH changes with our two acidity variables. The very pronounced pattern is the negative relationship between fixed.acidity and pH. But we also see that pH generally increases as volatile.acidity increases.

Multivariate Analysis

In the previous section we found that density has a negative correlation with quality, but here it seems that when alcohol is in the equation the effect reverses.

Most other features behave the same way as we saw in the bivariate section.

Final Plots and Summary

Plot One

This plot, though simple, is important as alcohol has the strongest correlation with quality among all the features we have.

We can clearly see that the wines with higher alcohol content are rated higher. The difference is particularly pronounced between categories 6+ and those below 6.

Plot Two

This plot shows the two features with the strongest correlation with quality, which means they probably are the best predictors of a wine quality we can find in this data set.

Plot Three

This plot is interesting in that we can see, contrary to what weve found in the bivariate analysis and correlation figures, once alcohol is accounted for, density seems to have a positive relationship with quality.

Reflection

I am somewhat surprised to find that the strongest predictor we have of quality, at least when used alone, is such a simple, measureable and easily observable feature as alcohol content.

As far as I know, it isnt extremely hard to increase the alcohol content by a a little when making wine. At least some of the makers who stop the fermentation early can stop doing that and let it finish?

But then it could be that some third factor causes both a higher alcohol content and better quality - imagine that better grapes make better wine, and better grapes are also suited to complete fermentation.

If there was such a factor, however, we cant find it in our dataset. Statistical modeling or machine learning techniques may provide more insights.
